inn1.comm: well, that was pretty erratic to start things off, but maybe because it's his first ball, he's been given the benefit of the doubt
better, straighter, and good carry as well
oops! That's almost Harmisonesque. Pitched on the white lines and swung towards the slips
wonderful response! Real pace, yorker length and inswinging. Joyce gets his bat down just in time
strays onto the pads and that's clipped firmly through midwicket to bring up the first boundary of the day. Good shot
banged in and bending back into the batsman. Joyce plays inside the line with a perpendicular bat
wild again. Arguably less wide than his first ball, but rightly called as Gilchrist takes in front of slip
leg-side again, and Joyce tickles the last ball down to fine leg. A woolly first over
good start, full length, curving in, defended on the front foot
gets it a fraction wrong this time. Loye flicks to leg to get off the mark
bit of width, but not too much. Strange call, to be honest
tighter, and just back of a length. Joyce plays inside the line again
good probing length outside the left-hander's off stump
no stroke offered as the ball fizzes through
curving towards the slips, and edged towards the gully. Safe though
big booming outswing from Tait. Useful pace as well. Loye leaves alone
starts on middle-and-leg, decent swing again, but easily clipped to midwicket
big appeal from Tait, but that looked to be sliding down leg. Loye was well squared up though. Hawkeye disagrees ...
fuller, outside off, and squirted to gully. Rapid
95mph, but misdirected, and slips past Loye's ribs for another extra
good pace again, Loye drawn into the drive, but controls his aggression
right up to the bat, and an inside-edge bobbles into the crease as Loye drives again. Better over
fizzes through, no stroke offered
probing, probing. No stroke again as the ball sits in the channel outside off stump
good discipline from Bracken.
outside off stump once again, Joyce shoulders arms once again
straighter, and this time Joyce is forced to defend. Drawn onto the front foot
excellent over. Joyce defends into the covers
banged in, takes the glove and dribbles into the covers. Good aggression
right up to the bat, hint of movement and watchfully defended back up the pitch
speared down the leg-side, takes the pad but Gilchrist runs round to field
attempted yorker, 90mph-plus but no movement, and easily squeezed to square leg
nicely timed through square leg, bit of a half-volley this time but Tait is finding a good rhythm after that erratic first over
booming full-toss, Loye flings the bat but the outswing deceives him and he under-edges into the slips.
a swish and a miss from Joyce - that was loose. Tempted by a hint of width, but good bounce and movement
dropped! And that was a dolly. Joyce's first attacking move of the match, danced down the track, had a smear, and Tait at deep point fluffed a sitter
outside off, tight call, but that won't improve Bracken's mood
tighter to the stumps and defended
fuller length, and pushed to leg
there he goes! It's that slog-sweep again, and it's a big, big six again! Slight top-edge, but what power! Twelve rows back, I reckon
back on a good length, and solidly defended
fancy that, it's a wide one, and he chased it!
shorter, quicker, but defended on the hop into the vacant gully. 97mph that one, and Loye is shaking his finger, as well he might
96.1mph now, and that climbs past the left-hander's edge for Gilchrist to take above his head
yorker! And a good one too. Hastily dug out by Joyce
swinging again, but a bit short and easily defended into the leg-side
right on the spot, swinging back towards off stump, and solidly pushed back up the pitch. Tidy stuff, and brutally quick as well!
leg-side, and turned away for a quick single
width, and smacked! That's a lovely shot - down the track, on the up, and over the covers
shorter but straighter, and turned to leg with no great pace
leg-sided again, clipped into space - in fact, it came off the pad but the intent was there
there's the sweep again! But this time it's a wild outside-edge that flies high over the slips. Still, it'll do
no edges this time! That's a fine sweep, fizzes through square leg to complete an expensive over!
94.9mph that time, but nicely timed even though the direction was lacking. Steered into the gully off the back foot
good yorker, squeezed out to the gully
slightly short, but rapid and Loye can't time his clip through leg
quick! Short and climbing at Loye, who fends this off his nose with a bit of discomfort
that's that tempter again, and Loye is drawn into it once again. Beaten by the swing, and just as well for his sake

much better shot, up towards the blockhole but swinging away. He didn't try to smack it, but it went like the proverbial through the covers all the same. When it's coming at you at 97mph, you don't need to have a mow!
right on the money first up. Defended, but there's no swing
there's the intent. Joyce takes a couple of steps but defends nonetheless. Wasn't quite there for the shot
short, and smeared through midwicket - that was a front-foot pull and it was hammered. Good batting
fuller, but well timed through midwicket again. Clipped rather than carved though
outside off, left alone
wider, and Loye flinches in his eagerness to have a mow, but managed to restrain himself
decent over for England
line and length, as you'd expect. Respectfully defended
same again. No pace, no movement, but just there
flashy flashy! It's that width again, and Loye just can't quite get it right with that shot. But it's too wide
straighter, and left alone
excellent line and length this time, and some big seam movement back towards the stumps. Loye leaves alone with a flourish
thunk! Good grief, down on the sweep, slight top-edge straight into the grille! McGrath looks as non-plussed as a fast bowler should when someone attempts to sweep them

GOT HIM! McGrath dropped it short, as he was bound to do, and Loye tried to keep things positive by playing the hook. But it was a stroke played with no conviction, and a steepling top-edge ended in the hands of deep square-leg!
off the mark straight away, but a bit of hesitation there! Tickled to leg but safely home
good length, and defended with a hint of inside-edge
clipped off the pads and another stuttering single. These two won't have batted together very often
just back of a length, defended with a loud "NO!"
outside off stump and played on the up to cover
drawn forward and played coolly into the covers. Solid over
probing line, just back of a length and angling across the left-hander. Defended off the back foot
straighter and squared up as Joyce attempts to work to leg
fizzes past the bat with a bit of cut and good carry
slightly wider but still in the channel. Left alone
starts outside leg but nips back to take the thigh pad
shorter, and that's an excellent swivel-pull to dent McGrath's ego at the end of the over
outside off stump once again. No great pace or movement
banged in a bit this time, but outside off again and left alone
wicket-to-wicket. Turned into the leg-side
on the money again. Defended into the covers
that one fizzed through! Lots of oohs and aahs, but no real alarms for Bell
attempted yorker, but easily driven out for a single to mid-on. Bell keeps the strike, which Australia might not mind too much
short and wide and deservedly timed through the covers. Bell didn't try to hit that too hard, just placed it behind point. Well played
short and wide again! Strangely erratic from McGrath, and Bell - perhaps astonished to get two such rank balls in succession hits this harder and in the air in front of point!
better line and length this time. A loud "NO!"
width but left alone. Sensible batting
shoulders arms again
a bit of a squelch as this one nips back to hit Bell amidships. He's not fussed though. Balls of steel
outside off, and nudged down to third man
good line and length to resume
lovely strike. Good stride and perfect placement, straight through extra cover
width, and a measured carve through point
defended into the covers, and a scampered single
dropped in a touch short, and this one is defended into the gully
bit of a fish outside off stump that time! It bent away from the bat at the last minute, and Bell was tempted. Still, he lives on
bit of nip again for McGrath - he's liking this track
again, good carry to the keeper from outside off stump. Joyce plays inside the line, as is his wont
shorter and straighter - defended off the back foot to point, and a loud "No!"
probing stuff, played with an angled bat into the gully
tries to turn this to leg, but slightly squared up
lovely strike. McGrath is serving up far too many four-balls by his own high standards. Width again, and cracked past point for another boundary
turned to leg, another loud call stops the single
line and length, respectfully defended
a fraction short, and Bell swings into a big ambitious pull over midwicket. Goes high, but well in front of the man in the deep. Decent shot
width, and slapped past point
straighter, and defended back down the pitch
pushed into the covers to complete another tidy over
oooh! Sawn in half by a big nip-backer. Passed through bat and midriff
fuller, and drawn forward to defend
strays down the leg side. Another extra
quick single from a nudge into the gully. The shy was way off target though
width, and nudged down to third man
tighter line, just back of a length. Joyce plays inside the line again
attacking intent - down the pitch to meet McGrath, and a leading edge deflects through point
good wheels, Stuey, good wheels. Right in the channel again
another nudge into the gully, and a near-miss on that quick single. Joyce forgot that Clarke is left-handed in the field, and that might have been out if he had hit!
slightly squared up, but safe
bang! Symonds takes out the leg stump at the non-striker's end, but Bell is home for another single
defended with an angled bat to point. The batsmen rotate the strike again
outside off stump, and left alone to finish
good swinging full length. Maybe not as sharp as his first spell, but rapid nonetheless. Nothing has dropped below 90mph yet (144kph)
outside off, driven without much power
short and swung into the leg-side. Cleaned up on the square-leg boundary
fuller length, and nicely timed down the ground by Bell.
that's a lovely strike from a man who's really starting to flourish now! Gave himself heaps of room by retreating to leg, and thwacked that through the covers. Nick Knight would be proud
banged in, swung away. A useful over for England
starts with a gentle leg-stump half-volley. Clipped away
"nice Pup!" says Gilchrist, good line and length, and flight too
paddle-sweep to fine leg. Good measured shot
clipped to leg
good flight, calm defence
drifted across Joyce, and that was a bit of a loose waft. And he knows it
strays onto the pads, clipped away
driven firmly but fielded in the followthrough by Tait
snorter! That was short, quick, straight, and vicious. Bell played it very well to be fair, watching closely and swaying out of line
tried to follow up with the yorker, but that was sprayed down leg. Nice idea, poorly executed
fuller but slightly off-line. Joyce can't get it away though
dabbed into the covers, and a scampered single
flapped out into the deep. Bit of a top-edge
defended into the covers
turned into the leg-side
another quick single into the covers
steps across his stumps and turns this to mid-on for another single. Good rotation of the strike
clipped into the deep to complete the over
turned to midwicket
firm clip to square leg
down on one knee, and drilled over square leg. Not quite timed though, and swept up on the boundary's edge
fuller length, and defended
couple of quick steps down the pitch to pick the gap
firmly driven into the covers
outside leg, takes the thigh pad, but that's another good quick single. Good communication
straighter and angled towards off stump. Defended back down the pitch
steered calmly to third man to bring up a very fine fifty for Ed Joyce. His second in consecutive matches. Well batted
leg-side again, and dabbed to midwicket
that's a lovely strike. Clip-driven, if you like, through midwicket all along the ground. Just picked up inside the rope
takes the pad, and that's the over
down on the sweep, and that's a thick inside-edge. Bit streaky, but gets away with it
reverse-sweep - or dab, rather, as he did nothing more than deflect the ball. Found the gap through backward square
excellent running between these two. Another dab to third man
leg-sided, misses out with a glance
good ball to finish, line and length and maybe even some spin
bit loose outside off stump. A dab and a miss
a swing and a miss to follow up - that was rash. Down the track and a big hoon over cow corner, but hit nothing but air
drawn forward with a defensive push, finds the gap
driven back down the ground, and that's quick work from Bracken! He fielded in his followthrough and Bell might have been out if his shy had hit
pushed out to point
another nudge towards the cordon. Steady stuff
sweet strike through extra-cover! That was a gentle loosener, but Joyce cracked it almost one-handed on the up!
dropped! In the air to his left, and Symonds grabs with his weaker hand. That was a slower delivery, but he should have got it. And he's cross
deflected behind square
another miss! That was an inside-edge onto the pads, and it bobbled past Gilchrist! Lucky, lucky
the end of an eventful over, now here's Cameron White.
good start, nice flight, nice line
"bowled Barry!" says Gilchrist, and he's right
strays onto leg this time
Joyce plays for non-existent spin, and uncomfortably so
clipped into the leg-side
good finish, Joyce leaves alone outside off stump
shot! Drifts onto the pads, and that's clipped up and over midwicket for another boundary
more good scampering brings up the hundred stand. Well played chaps
played through leg again. Some easy pickings at the moment
clipped off the pads. Good batting
better line and length. Defended
down on the sweep again, and good contact as well. Nine off the over
loose again. Short, rank and leg-sided. Bell misses with his swing, but so does Gilchrist with his take
loose again. Not good bowling
driven down the ground, and that's Bell's fifty - his first against Australia. Well played
excellent rotation of the strike
tighter now, after those loose early deliveries
and the drinks break brings a breakthrough once again! And it's that old shark McGrath who does the job. It was short, Bell went for a big swing, and Gilchrist steadied himself under a big top-edge
short again
outside off, and Flintoff drives off the back foot into the covers
tighter to off stump, and defended
in that corridor of uncertainty again, and dabbed to point
Joyce down the track and pads it back
again pad, and this time a loud appeal as well. Nothing doing there, though
swept to deep square leg, good tag fielding on the rope from Bracken and Clarke
swept again, straight to the man in the deep so only ever one
steps back and punches to mid-on
turned straight to Symonds at midwicket
Joyce back and defends
steered into the slips and slap bang into the one man there ...he's at third slip
same shot, but this time Joyce finds the gap and ambles a single as third man fields
Flintoff cramped as he looks to thwack into the off and he can only push the ball to point
this time he steps back and finds more room, punching it wide of cover to the man in the deep
short, pulled to deep midwicket
Joyce fails to time an attempted swat into the off side
White drifts to leg and Joyce sweeps
Flintoff works the ball to square leg, the man is right back and so they run two with some ease
Flintoff back, it hits him high up and the immediate thought was that it might have been going over the top. It pitched in line and was certainly straight ... is this the start of England's wobble?
confident start, short and he pulls through midwicket
clipped away into the leg side
straight, Strauss defends solidly and correctly
banged in, Strauss who was looking to come down the pitch, plays a rather hurried swat-pull, under control and down to long leg
pushed into the leg side ... fielders converge but it's well placed and they can't prevent the single
into the off side but not timed
forward, he shapes to play at one leaving him outside off stump but changes his mind at the last moment and pulls out of the shot
cut off the top edge through the slips and Tait gets his body in the line at third man
very wide outside off stump ... Stevie Wonder would have spotted that one
clipped into space on the leg
chopped down into the pitch a few oohs as it bobbles close to the stumps
cut into the off side
too much width and that allows Strauss to cut the ball behind square on the off
driven through the covers to the deep
steps back and plops it into the off
Strauss back, drops it at his feet and Clark scurries down the track to prevent any thoughts of a single
... and so Clark serves him one on the leg which he whips through midwicket
short, pulled but straight into the ground ... net result still a single, as it would have been had he middled it
driven to the sweeper
at last ...Joyce steps down the track and gives himself room to drive on the up over mid-off
turned off his hips to midwicket
fullish, dug out to midwicket
full again, driven with timing and Hayden's dive at wide long-on is to no avail as his dive came too late and he carried the ball over with him
tighter line and no run there
Strauss steps to off and works to deep long-on ...good running and when they saw it was Tait in the deep they came back for the second
flicked into the off side this time
full toss driven at - and through -Symonds at extra cover. Ironic cheers from the crowd as Symonds looks as bewildered as a man whose pocket has just been picked
wide and left alone
two steps, one to leg, and that is crashed through cover and it races to the rope
pushed to Symonds at extra cover and ironic cheers as he stops it. Symonds scowls ..he certainly is not amused
straight, Strauss, again on the walk, bat-pads it and keep running
Joyce with < footwork finally has to stretch to squeeze the ball over Glenn McGrath at point ... yes, at point ... and it is well stopped by Tait in the deep
pushed into the off side off his pads as Strauss nicks the strike
smacked to mid-on who is two-thirds of the way back
driven with real oomph past the bowler and deep mid-off fields well

well, not a dismissal you'll see in a Test. Strauss walks right across his stumps and scoops the ball to leg ... it goes straight up and Clark only has to move eight or nine yards at backward square leg to take a sitter
angled bat and the ball is run to the left of third man, nice placement
whipped from middle stump to square leg
defended to mid-off
pushed into space, ambled single, you know the drill
and again, no real pressure on the new man from the fielding side
flicked to square leg
full toss patted to deep cover where Tait again makes a hash of some simple fielding. If he was trying to work his way out of a trip to the Caribbean he couldn't do a better job than he is today
blocked and Clark quick to field it as he dribbles back towards him
squirted to third man, a half appeal from Clark but more in frustration than expectation
superb shot, gives himself room and creams that between midwicket and mid-on
less impressive, slashed in the air a couple of yards short of the incoming third man
Tait follows Dalrymple as he moves to leg, but he still gets it into a gap
Joyce aims a big heave-pull and gets it fine on the leg side. Warm applause from the crowd for his maiden ODI hundred and the fourth one-day hundred of his career
patted into the off side
Dalrymple steps to leg, Tait goes to the off and at full stretch the batsman eases it over point and it races to the rope
worked to the sweeper
great shot from Dalrymple, driven off one knee through extra cover
pushed up to mid-off for a strolled one
driven to mid-on
driven down the ground to mid-off
dropped into the leg side and another straightforward single to end Clark's spell
full toss driven at mid-off who fields on the bounce

banged in, Joyce plays a tired pull which he doesn't get hold of and the ball loops to wide midwicket. A great ovation as he walks off. His innings has  given England something to bowl at and also ensured that John Buchanan gets his wish of making sure Australia are in a game at last
Dalrymple moves to leg, swishes and misses. That was 93mph (150kph) which is pretty remarkable at this stage with an old ball
full toss, absolutely hammered to McGrath at sweeper where he makes a good stop
short, Nixon hooks and gets a top edge over Gilchrist for four
another one banged in,  and this time Nixon plays a really nothing semi-pull shot which lobs to extra cover. A short and certainly not sweet stay.
short and Dalrymple swings and misses
short of a length outside off stump, and another swing and miss from Dalrymple

yet again banged in but this time Dalrymple on it quickly and it goes all the way over midwicket ...it only just carries and it's dropped by the spectator leaning over the fence ...Tait's family enclosure?
McGrath responds with a yorker which Dalrymple hammers down the ground
full toss and smashed wide of midwicket where it evades the desperate dive of White
driven to long-on, the two players get in a real mess over the second and both end up at the bowler's end ... Dalrymple goes but surely Bopara should have sacrificed himself
short and wide down the leg side
glanced to long leg
two steps and sliced to third man
bobbled into the off side and a scampered single as Tait fields
sweet one-day shot, opens the face of the bat and uses Tait's pace to the full as the ball is angled through second slip
bumbled into the leg side
Plunkett aims to run the ball through the slips but misses
full, good ball which Bopara can only dig out
full toss which Bopara looks to swing to leg, gets a leading edge and the ball hangs in the air before dropping feet in front of White racing in to mid-off
short and Plunkett looks surprised that it was not called wide. He has a point, but as long as the umpires are consistent it doesn't matter
driven uppishly to long-off and Bopara runs well to the danger end for a second
overpitched and Plunkett smacks it over wide long-on for a one-bounce four
yorker, well dug out towards extra cover and a single to end

inn2.comm: what a start! Brilliant, brilliant delivery from Plunkett. Full, fast, inswinging, perfect yorker length, and Gilchrist has no answer whatsoever! Well, well ... England are on a roll!
signs of swing for Plunkett, though this one is shorter in length and outside off
ripper! Late boomeranging movement and that hoops round the edge of the bat. No foot movement there
more handy swing, but started wider this time. Feisty first over so far
too much swing that time, and rightly called wide. But this is encouraging for England
that's a harsh call. And Nixon behind the stumps mutters his indignation
first runs off the bat, pushed into the covers
good line, shorter in length, Hayden lets it swing by. Excellent first over
full in length, bit of movement, clipped square
erratic - started outside off and swung further away
GOTTIM! Well, well, what a start from England! Shorter and straighter, Hodge tried to leave alone but it was onto him too quickly and a big inside-edge deflected onto his middle stump!
oops, wide and wider
straighter this time. Pushed back down the pitch
good discipline
good line and length - left alone to finish a successful over
good pace and sharp nip off the track. Hayden is squared up and hit in the midriff
good length - slightly fuller
drifting down leg, and deflects away for a single
sharp pace, nips away late
excellently timed off the legs. Panesar at fine leg can't cut that off and that's Australia's first boundary of the innings
drifts onto the legs, and clipped down to fine leg - where the substitute Chris Read fields! Blimey, we'd forgotten he was still here!
left alone. Clarke needs to be watchful
right back and into line
pushed into the covers
strays in line again
and that's gone too fine for Read at fine leg to cut off. Another boundary and Hayden's first
that's gone fine as well, and Monty Panesar produces a sprawling fumbled stop at fine leg to cut off the boundary. There's no faulting his effort
back of a length but straighter and swinging back in. Left alone
good probing stuff. There's some nice trampoline bounce for the seamers outside off stump
carbon copy of the last two balls. Plunkett's using his height well, and Hayden leaves alone
a bit wider, but still no shot offered
less threatening now. Too short and too wide, but Hayden's not tempted
decent line and length, but Clarke's not troubled
beats the infield with a firm push through the covers
shoulders arms once again. Cagey stuff from Australia so far
too straight, and angling onto the legs, clipped very firmly to deep midwicket, where Panesar fields just inside the rope
and now leg-sided to the left-hander as well. Too short too, and clipped square
fuller and wider, Hayden drives but short cover fields well and threatens a shy at the non-striker's end
short but straight. Defended into the gully
too short again. Clarke pushes into the covers and sets off at once. Bell at cover shies underarm but misses
outside off stump, and left alone
a fraction fuller, but still not tempting the stroke. That glorious first delivery seems a bit distant now
short again, and helped down to fine leg
that's the spot. Fuller, straighter, and swinging late. Clarke is properly beaten
outside off again. Left alone again
fuller and straighter, Hayden gets everything behind it and pushes out to midwicket
floated up to a yorker length, dug out well
good discipline. Hayden comes forward and pushes this to cover
thwack! A couple of steps and whipped through midwicket with a lot of bottom hand. Bounces just inside the rope. Good selective batting
looking again, but nothing doing. Defended back down the ground
short, and Clarke turns turtle. Nixon gathers high above his head
outside off stump, left alone again
flicked round the corner, and another quick single
fuller, and defended into the covers. That's a better length
strays down leg
width, and steered to a tumbling gully
fuller and pushed back down the ground
on the pads but clipped to midwicket with no great power
down the leg-side. These extras are adding up
left alone outside off. Better line this time
defended out to midwicket
driven firmly to mid-off. Ricochets off Mahmood's knee but good old Monty is on hand to clean up
ooh, a bit lucky there! A leading edge looped up in the air, but Flintoff couldn't get there in time
short and outside off, steered into the gully
a bit of an appeal there from Nixon, but umpire Harper isn't won over. Another wide!
good delivery - fuller and bends round the edge of Clarke's bat. Six of those an over would suit England
leading edge again, but safe
thick outside edge to gully. Plunkett is struggling a bit with his action, but he's persevering
that one went wrong for Plunkett. Dragged down, wide of off stump, and flailed over point
better line and length. Fuller and straighter, and defended
outside off and left alone again
too much width again, but Hayden doesn't chase it
better line. Much tighter to off stump, and Hayden shoulders arms
still no shot being offered. Good disciplined line and length
left alone again. Lots of dot balls
smacked to long-on, stopped inches inside the rope
edged into his body, a yes-no moment and then they scurry through
awful dismissal!  that was wide, got wider and Clarke needed an extension to reach it and Nixon dived in front of slip to hold a good catch. England get lucky ...
defended back to the bowler
bosh! that's thwacked over midwicket for a vast six
tickled into the leg side
tossed up, driven to long-on
crikey - this is too exciting. Right, massive apologies for all the nonsense just gone by. We are back up and running. I hope ...
and that's Matthew Hayden's fifty. Well batted. Slow at first, but increasingly brutal
too much width, and that's carved down to third man
thumped over point! Gave himself room and threw the kitchen sink at that. A one-bounce four, inches inside the rope
something's not right about Symonds' bicep. I think he's tweaked it playing that last carve over point
short and wild down the leg-side. Symonds flexes some more

there's the breakthrough! And it's that man on the drive who does the trick. Lots of width from Mahmood, Hayden went for a big booming drive and it's a smart reflex take from Jamie Dalrymple at short cover! Not the best ball, but the best result as far as England are concerned
full and swinging onto off stump. Squirted to gully
Hussey still not off the mark, and that's the end of an important over
pushed insouciantly down the ground. The batsmen jog a leisurely single
clipped back down the track, wide of a diving Panesar for another single
on a good length, gentle turn but tight line. Pushed back to the bowler
another nudged single, down to long-on
tidy stuff, turned to midwicket to complete a fine over
skiddy swingy stuff from Bopara, and there's a call for a replay as Nixon whips the bails off. Not out, but sharp work nonetheless
nice line and length, and quite possibly sharper than he looks as well. Defended
lalalalala ... I'll just wibble away to myself for another over while our feed screws up again
good trading of singles
tidy stuff from Panesar. Shambolic stuff from ... ahem ... us. But ho hum, what can we do? Sorry about all this
bouncer from Bopara, but Nixon was standing up to the stumps ... so he had no chance. Still, White's not wearing a helmet, so he's asking for it really
nudged into the covers to get off the mark
tight bowling, a hint of swing
beautiful ball! Hits the seam, bounces sharply and cramps Hussey for room, and he chops it onto his stumps! That could well be game, set and match!
lovely ball! Hits the seam and fizzes past the edge. A pat of appreciation from Bell
great over from Bopara. This boy's got a bit about him with the ball
pushed into the covers
looking to drive on the up. Outside edge down to third man
full face of the bat in defence
straight to the fielder in the covers
beaten and well beaten outside off stump
tossed up, driven into the covers, a bit of a fumble and they come through for the single
inside-edged to square leg
good line and length again. Defended
a big appeal but that was sliding down leg. Good wicket-to-wicket bowling though
sharp and tight, lively stuff
pushed onto the back foot, glanced to fine leg
too much width this time and firmly cut, but cleaned up on the cover boundary
probing stuff from Panesar, defended
pushed into the covers for a scampered single
